<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title><![CDATA[Blog – Jiří Pudil]]></title><description><![CDATA[A full-stack web developer from Brno]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz</link><generator>GatsbyJS</generator><lastBuildDate>Fri, 17 Jun 2022 01:40:38 GMT</lastBuildDate><item><title><![CDATA[Your application needs a clock]]></title><description><![CDATA[Previously, I've discussed working with date and time values both server- and client-side, and I've covered storing temporal data in databases. This time, we're going to talk about telling time.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/your-application-needs-clock</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/your-application-needs-clock</guid><pubDate>Thu, 10 Mar 2022 09:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Storing dates and times in databases: the painless way]]></title><description><![CDATA[I've already talked about working with date and time values on both sides of the web stack. However, in web development, we not only manipulate temporal values, we often need to store them somewhere and retrieve them later. This post discusses the best methods of persisting dates and times in databases.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/storing-dates-times-in-databases-painlessly</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/storing-dates-times-in-databases-painlessly</guid><pubDate>Thu, 03 Mar 2022 07:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Beyond Date: bulletproof date and time API in JavaScript]]></title><description><![CDATA[I've talked about date and time not being easy in PHP, and it's not easier in JavaScript either. Luckily, similarly to the PHP ecosystem, the community has provided better solutions to date and time than the native <code>Date</code>. Let's discuss them.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/beyond-date</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/beyond-date</guid><pubDate>Sat, 30 Oct 2021 19:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Beyond DateTime: a domain-driven approach to date and time]]></title><description><![CDATA[Time is omnipresent in software development. Pretty much every web application works with it in one way or another. Even the simplest blogging platform stores "when" a post should be published and then displays and sorts them using that information. While you might not run into any issues when developing a blogging platform, any more complex system can easily expose how complicated time actually is. Because time <em>is</em> complicated. And yet, many standard libraries in programming languages only give us a limited arsenal to tackle it.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/beyond-datetime-domain-driven-approach</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/beyond-datetime-domain-driven-approach</guid><pubDate>Fri, 21 May 2021 08:30:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Services don't need names]]></title><description><![CDATA[I love Nette Framework's dependency injection solution. I really do. This post is here to share this passion, explaining why I think it is the best DI solution in today's PHP ecosystem.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/di-services-do-not-need-names</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/di-services-do-not-need-names</guid><pubDate>Fri, 12 Feb 2021 12:02:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Don't bring your own HTTP client]]></title><description><![CDATA[If you are developing a library that needs to make HTTP requests, here's how not to make it difficult for your consumers.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/do-not-bring-your-own-http-client</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/do-not-bring-your-own-http-client</guid><pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2020 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Body parser middleware that has your back]]></title><description><![CDATA[If you've ever implemented an HTTP API in PHP, you probably know that there's one thing you have to do over and over and over: parse the request body and validate the resulting structure. Now that we have PSR-15, let's use a middleware for that!]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/body-parser-middleware-that-has-your-back</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/body-parser-middleware-that-has-your-back</guid><pubDate>Tue, 28 Jan 2020 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Don't just float, swim with the floating point]]></title><description><![CDATA[They say you should understand floating-point precision by 35.0000000000014. This post is here to help you: it discusses how floats are (im)precise and why, demonstrates the problems you inevitably encounter when doing math with floats, and presents ways to prevent those problems by using more proper data types and structures.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/dont-just-float-swim-with-the-floating-point</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/dont-just-float-swim-with-the-floating-point</guid><pubDate>Fri, 07 Jun 2019 12:45:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[The frameworkless application]]></title><description><![CDATA[There's a new buzzword on the PHP block: frameworkless. The activities of PHP communities last year made it possible to build robust applications, uniquely composed of little bits, without relying on a big framework. Let's find out how they work and if it's a good approach.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/frameworkless-application</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/frameworkless-application</guid><pubDate>Thu, 31 Jan 2019 14:55:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Keeping your dependencies up-to-date]]></title><description><![CDATA[As the business requirements grow, so does the list of dependencies. Managers ask for a new feature, you just composer-require this thing and that other thing, and wire it into the application. But how do you keep track of new features in the dependencies? Or bugfixes? Or, most importantly, security patches?!]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/keeping-your-dependencies-up-to-date</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/keeping-your-dependencies-up-to-date</guid><pubDate>Fri, 14 Sep 2018 11:25:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[What's new in Naja 1.1.0]]></title><description><![CDATA[In the course of the last few weeks, I have invested some time into Naja. You might recall my previous announcement in which I stated that there was still one big thing left to do. Well, now it is done!]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/what-is-new-in-naja-1-1-0</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/what-is-new-in-naja-1-1-0</guid><pubDate>Fri, 27 Oct 2017 19:08:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Naja 1.0.0 released]]></title><description><![CDATA[Almost six months ago, I have released an alpha version of a new, modern AJAX library for Nette Framework named Naja. Now, after half a year in the wild production environment, I guess the time has come for a stable version.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/naja-1-0-0-released</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/naja-1-0-0-released</guid><pubDate>Sun, 10 Sep 2017 16:50:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Clock needs an interface]]></title><description><![CDATA[Almost every application needs to work with time: if not for some greater purpose like expiring access credentials, entities usually store information about when they were created or generally when something happened. Telling time is indeed a crucial responsibility, and being able to rely on the mechanism across the whole codebase is really important. But it can get problematic.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/clock-needs-an-interface</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/clock-needs-an-interface</guid><pubDate>Tue, 23 May 2017 15:50:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Nette Tester plugin for PhpStorm: 2.0.0 and beyond]]></title><description><![CDATA[A few minutes ago, I have released a total rework of my intellij-nette-tester plugin that integrates Nette Tester into PhpStorm.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/nette-tester-plugin-for-phpstorm-2-and-beyond</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/nette-tester-plugin-for-phpstorm-2-and-beyond</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 May 2017 16:20:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Announcing three new open-source projects]]></title><description><![CDATA[I've had a really productive couple of weeks and (mostly) weekends recently. I've worked extensively on one of my side projects using modern JS stack including Webpack, faced issues here and there, and found a way to solve them. In the end, I proudly announce three new open-source packages: a modern AJAX library for Nette Framework, Neon loader for Webpack, and a library integrating the Webpack build process into Nette-powered applications.]]></description><link>https://jiripudil.cz/blog/announcing-three-new-open-source-projects</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://jiripudil.cz/blog/announcing-three-new-open-source-projects</guid><pubDate>Mon, 27 Mar 2017 08:00:00 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>